{{wikipedia}}
==English==

===Etymology===
{{Gr.}} ''[[Ουρανός]]''<!--Ουρανός--> (ouranos), heaven, sky.  The [[planet]] was formerly named [[Georium Sidus]] after George III, but subsequently renamed after '''Uranus''' (see below).

===Pronunciation===
*[[RP]]: {{IPAchar|/ˈjʊrənəs/}} ''or'' {{IPAchar|/jʊˈreɪnəs/}}
*[[WEAE]]: {{IPAchar|/ˈjurənəs/}} ''or'' {{IPAchar|/juˈreɪnəs/}}
*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-eɪnəs|-eɪnəs]]

===Proper noun===
'''Uranus''' ''m'', genitive '''Urani'''

Second declension

#<!--GreekDeitySkyHeaven-->{{Greek mythology}} The god of the sky and heavens, son and husband to [[Gaia]], with whom he fathered the [[Titans]] and the [[Cyclops]]
#<!--Planet7-->{{astronomy}} The seventh [[planet]] in our [[solar system]], discovered in 1781 by Sir William Herschell and called [[Herschel]] until the mid-19th century. Uranus has fifteen moons.

